                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d431">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">662.6331/78: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Belgium</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gibson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Brussels</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-03-31T14:00:00+00:00"
                            >March 31, 1931—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 31—1:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>22. Department’s 15, March 30, 1 p.m. I am advised by the Foreign Office that,
                    when the Belgo-Luxemburg customs union was established in 1921, Belgium had
                    commercial treaties containing unconditional most-favored-nation clauses with
                    France, Great Britain, and the Netherlands. If there were others, the Foreign
                    Office will give me that information at a later date.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gibson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
